<text top="41" left="382" width="172" height="10" font="font1" id="p1_t2" reading_order_no="1" segment_no="1" tag_type="text">http://www.filariajournal.com/content/4/1/10</text>
<text top="756" left="508" width="46" height="10" font="font1" id="p1_t3" reading_order_no="71" segment_no="12" tag_type="text">Page 4 of 6<b>4</b></text>
<text top="769" left="432" width="122" height="8" font="font3" id="p1_t4" reading_order_no="72" segment_no="13" tag_type="text">(page number not for citation purposes)</text>
<text top="639" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t5" reading_order_no="11" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">as each other, whereas in the 4A+XY species the four auto-</text>
<text top="651" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t6" reading_order_no="12" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">somes and the Y-chromosome are of comparable size,</text>
<text top="662" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t7" reading_order_no="13" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">whereas the X-chromosome (which would be an X-auto-<i>(page number not for citation purposes)</i></text>
<text top="674" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t8" reading_order_no="14" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">some fusion product) is visibly larger. The 3A+XY karyo-</text>
<text top="686" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t9" reading_order_no="15" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">type observed in O. volvulus and O. gibsoni is likely to have</text>
<text top="698" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t10" reading_order_no="16" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">been derived from the 4A+XY karyotype by a fusion</text>
<text top="709" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t11" reading_order_no="17" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">between two autosomes [12]. The relative sizes of the dif-</text>
<text top="721" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t12" reading_order_no="18" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">ferent chromosomes are consistent with this hypothesis in</text>
<text top="87" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t13" reading_order_no="19" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">that one of the autosomes is clearly the largest chromo-<i>O. volvulus </i></text>
<text top="98" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t14" reading_order_no="20" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">some, and presumably the autosome-autosome fusion</text>
<text top="110" left="313" width="36" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t15" reading_order_no="21" segment_no="2" tag_type="text">product.<i>O. gibsoni </i></text>
<text top="134" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t16" reading_order_no="22" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">The pattern of karyotype evolution (Figure 2) is likely to</text>
<text top="145" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t17" reading_order_no="23" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">reflect organismal evolution and indicate taxonomic rela-</text>
<text top="157" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t18" reading_order_no="24" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">tionships. All species of filarioids which have been exam-<a href=""> [12</a>]. The relative sizes of the dif-</text>
<text top="169" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t19" reading_order_no="25" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">ined for their chromosomes are from the family</text>
<text top="181" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t20" reading_order_no="26" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">Onchocercidae, and from three subfamilies, Setariinae</text>
<text top="192" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t21" reading_order_no="27" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">( Seteria spp), Dirofilariinae ( Dirofilaria and Loa ) and</text>
<text top="204" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t22" reading_order_no="28" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">Onchocercinae (all other species in Table 1). The pre-</text>
<text top="216" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t23" reading_order_no="29" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">sumed ancestral state (5A+X0) occurs in the Setariinae,<a href="">igure 2) </a>is likely to</text>
<text top="228" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t24" reading_order_no="30" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">most of the Onchocercinae and Loa loa (but not Diro-</text>
<text top="239" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font5" id="p1_t25" reading_order_no="31" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">filaria ). Current phylogenetic opinion has been unable to</text>
<text top="251" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t26" reading_order_no="32" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">resolve the major clades of the Onchocercinae, which</text>
<text top="263" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t27" reading_order_no="33" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">reduce to a star polytomy [28]. Loa forms a clade from this</text>
<text top="275" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t28" reading_order_no="34" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">unresolved polytomy, but Dirofilaria is consistently</text>
<text top="286" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t29" reading_order_no="35" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">grouped along the Onchocerca clade. The reduction to<i>Seteria </i></text>
<text top="298" left="313" width="242" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t30" reading_order_no="36" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">4A+XY has occurred in both Dirofilaria and Onchocerca ,</text>
<text top="310" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t31" reading_order_no="37" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">and hence it supports the molecular data, but it also indi-<i>Dirofilaria </i></text>
<text top="322" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t32" reading_order_no="38" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">cates that the Onchocerca / Dirofilaria clade is most closely</text>
<text top="333" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t33" reading_order_no="39" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">related to the Wuchereria / Brugia clade because it is found<i>Loa</i></text>
<text top="345" left="313" width="34" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t34" reading_order_no="40" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">in both.</text>
<text top="369" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t35" reading_order_no="41" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">The observation that O. volvulus apparently shares the<a href=""> 1). T</a>he pre-</text>
<text top="380" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t36" reading_order_no="42" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">same karyotype as O. gibsoni , but not O. ochengi or O.</text>
<text top="392" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font5" id="p1_t37" reading_order_no="43" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">dukei , might be taken as evidence for a close phylogenetic</text>
<text top="404" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t38" reading_order_no="44" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">relationship, and Muller [29] also considered that O. vol-<i>Loa loa </i></text>
<text top="416" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font5" id="p1_t39" reading_order_no="45" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">vulus was most closely related to O. gibsoni on the basis of</text>
<text top="427" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t40" reading_order_no="46" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">the structure of the cuticle. However, Bain [30] held that<i>Diro-</i></text>
<text top="439" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font5" id="p1_t41" reading_order_no="47" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">O. volvulus was taxonomically more closely related to O.<i>filaria</i></text>
<text top="451" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font5" id="p1_t42" reading_order_no="48" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">ochengi , and recent molecular phylogeny reconstruction</text>
<text top="463" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t43" reading_order_no="49" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">using the 12s, 16s and ND5 mitochondrial genes very</text>
<text top="474" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t44" reading_order_no="50" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">strongly supports this view (Morales Hojas, Cheke and<a href="">28]. </a></text>
<text top="486" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t45" reading_order_no="51" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">Post, unpublished data). If this is true, it would indicate<i>Loa </i></text>
<text top="498" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t46" reading_order_no="52" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">that the similar karyotypes of O. volvulus and O. gibsoni</text>
<text top="510" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t47" reading_order_no="53" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">have been produced by two different fusion events (which</text>
<text top="521" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t48" reading_order_no="54" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">may not even have involved the same pairs of autosomes),<i>Dirofilaria </i></text>
<text top="533" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t49" reading_order_no="55" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">and this is likely to be reflected in the precise position of</text>
<text top="545" left="313" width="219" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t50" reading_order_no="56" segment_no="6" tag_type="text">the translocation breakpoints at the molecular level.</text>
<text top="569" left="313" width="241" height="10" font="font6" id="p1_t51" reading_order_no="57" segment_no="7" tag_type="title">B-chromosomes and nucleolus organising region<i>Onchocerca </i></text>
<text top="580" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t52" reading_order_no="58" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">Both O. volvulus and O. gibsoni have B-chromosomes</text>
<text top="592" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t53" reading_order_no="59" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">[12,14]. These are supernumery chromosomes which are</text>
<text top="604" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t54" reading_order_no="60" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">not present in every individual, and when they are present<i>Dirofilaria </i></text>
<text top="615" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t55" reading_order_no="61" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">they can be haploid, diploid, triploid, tetraploid, etc, in</text>
<text top="627" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t56" reading_order_no="62" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">different individuals. The origin and subsequent evolu-<i>Onchocerca</i></text>
<text top="639" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t57" reading_order_no="63" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">tion of B-chromosomes is a long-standing problem in</text>
<text top="651" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t58" reading_order_no="64" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">genetics [31]. B-chromosomes can have definite pheno-</text>
<text top="662" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t59" reading_order_no="65" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">typic affects, but it has always been unclear whether this</text>
<text top="674" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t60" reading_order_no="66" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">was the result of specific genes or a mere consequence of<i>Onchocerca</i></text>
<text top="686" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t61" reading_order_no="67" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">the presence of an extra chromosome. It is largely</text>
<text top="698" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t62" reading_order_no="68" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">unknown whether B-chromosomes carry genes and<i>Dirofilaria </i></text>
<text top="709" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t63" reading_order_no="69" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">whether those genes are repeated elsewhere in the more</text>
<text top="721" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t64" reading_order_no="70" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">constant part of the genome. In any case, if the origin of</text>
<text top="199" left="55" width="134" height="9" font="font7" id="p1_t65" reading_order_no="3" segment_no="4" tag_type="title">Litomosoides sigmodontis karyotype<i>Wuchereria</i></text>
<text top="199" left="55" width="37" height="9" font="font9" id="p1_t66" reading_order_no="2" segment_no="4" tag_type="title">Figure 1</text>
<text top="210" left="55" width="225" height="9" font="font10" id="p1_t67" reading_order_no="4" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">Litomosoides sigmodontis karyotype. Aceto-orcein stained<i>Brugia </i></text>
<text top="221" left="55" width="239" height="9" font="font11" id="p1_t68" reading_order_no="5" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">spermatozoa from the seminal receptacle of an adult female</text>
<text top="231" left="55" width="209" height="9" font="font11" id="p1_t69" reading_order_no="6" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">worm, showing five or six condensed chromosomes</text>
